== Insider Tips from a Local

#tip-box[
  *Conventionné vs. Non-Conventionné*: When choosing a doctor or specialist, check if they are "conventionné". This means they adhere to the official government-set fees, so your out-of-pocket cost will be minimal and predictable. A "non-conventionné" doctor can set their own prices, which will be higher, and your reimbursement will still be based on the official rate, leaving you with a larger bill.
]

#tip-box[
  *The Magic Mailbox*: Every mutuelle office has a secure, 24/7 mailbox. There's no need to wait in line during office hours just to submit your reimbursement forms. Simply stick on your vignette and drop the form in the box anytime. It’s a small but very convenient part of the system.
]

#tip-box[
  *Hospital Invoices*: Unlike a GP visit, you typically do not pay for a hospital stay upfront. The hospital will bill your mutuelle directly for the covered portion, and then send you an invoice for your share of the costs weeks or even months later. Don't be surprised when it arrives!
]

#tip-box[
  *Don't Be Shy to Ask*: Especially in Brussels and other large cities, a high percentage of healthcare professionals speak excellent English. When calling to make an appointment, it's perfectly acceptable to start the conversation with, "Hello, do you speak English?" You will almost always get a helpful response.
]

